UV–Vis spectroscopy and fluorescence spectroscopy were utilized to understand the Optical properties of C-Dots as synthesized by varying temperature and time (Table 1
                        ). The UV–Vis spectra of g-CD which was synthesized via hydrothermal reaction maintained at 175 °C exhibited an absorption band at 281 nm whereas the same absorption band for b-CD was observed at 275 nm when synthesized at 200 °C in an autoclave for 16 or 24 h (Fig. 3
                        ). These characteristic absorption bands obtained for both the C-Dots accounted for the π-π* transition of C = C making the core of C-Dots. The redshift was observed in the case of g-CD when compared to b-CD was deemed to be the surface functionalization by oxygen-containing functional groups which possibly led to the reduction of the energy gap between HOMO and LUMO. Furthermore, such functional groups might have created numerous surface defects, leading to the formation of excitons i.e., combination of electron and holes, and presumably, these multiple PL centres would have resulted in green colour emissions.

The photoluminescence measurements of g-CD and b-CD revealed the emission properties of C-Dots and we have performed detailed experiments to understand the nature of emission. The excitations were made at different excitation wavelengths ranging from 240 nm to 400 nm with the interval of 20 nm i.e., 240, 260, 280, 300, 320, 340, 360, 380 and 400. The PL results showed that both g-CD and b-CD exhibited excitation-dependent emission with maximum emission at 426 nm and 420 nm respectively when excited at an excitation wavelength of 360 nm (Fig. 4
                        ). When the excitation wavelength increased from 240 nm to 400 nm the emission peak showed a bathochromic shift. This large shift in the emission peak is the signature of the different excited states of the C-Dots on the excitation wavelength which accounted for the surface defects arising due to varying degrees of carbonization [30]. The degree of carbonization tailored the surface defects as well as the size of the C-Dots [27]. In both CDs, the carbon backbone and attached functional groups introduced abundant structural configurations that led to various electronic structures and electronic transitions. Thus, these electronic transitions have created the possibility of electron-cloud overlaps, splitting the intrinsic energy levels and possibly generating sub-levels. In addition to this, at different excitation wavelengths, discrete transition modes had various probabilities, yet high energy gets absorbed in the specific region [21 31]. Thus, these transition possibilities emerged as emission wavelength shifts and changes in the PL intensity [32]. Depending on the degree of carbonization, g-CD has more hydroxyl groups compared to b-CD. The degree of variation in intraspecific morphology resulted in wide distribution of different energy levels and multiple PL centres [33 34], which not only impacted the PL property but also the solubility of C-Dots in organic solvents [35]. The C-Dots were found to be soluble in the organic solvents of high dielectric constant. Further to understand the photostability of C-Dots, the UV–Vis spectra were recorded after two months and the results were found to be astonishing. We didn’t observe any substantial decrease in intensity of emission even after gap of 60 days without the aid of any added stabilizer which accounted for their photostable nature as shown in Fig. 5
                        .

In order to optimize the reaction time and temperature in terms of Photoluminescence quantum yield (PLQY), we utilized a reference method where L-tryptophan was chosen to be reference. The PLQY of g-CDs i.e., CD synthesized at 175 °C for 16/24 h was calculated to be 7% and 8% respectively, whereas, the quantum yield of b-CD synthesized at 200 °C for 16/24 h was 10% and 13% respectively. The results thus further rationalized the significant effect of time and temperature of hydrothermal reaction over the optical features of natural source-derived C-Dots. Likewise, the lifetime of both the C-Dots was calculated using three similar exponential components, and this behaviour of the lifetime was indicating the presence of multiple emissive sites (Fig. 6
                        ). The calculated value of average fluorescence lifetimes of g-CD and b-CD were 0.99 and 0.51 ns respectively when excited at the wavelength of 284 nm (Table 2
                        ). The significantly low value of the PL lifetime of b-CD when compared to g-CD further demonstrated the presence of more trapping sites on the surface of g-CD [36 37]. The results were found to be consistent with the literature which implied that PL lifetime is shorter when emission occurred from a high energy excited state as compared to the emission from a short energy excited state [21]. Thus, the TRPL results established the fact that the carbon core, as well as the functional group on the surface of the C-Dots, created diverse PL centres.
